# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Repo Doctor — Antigravity Coding Conventions
#
# This file is read by the Antigravity AI assistant and tells it how to write
# code for this specific project.  Treat it like a team coding standards doc.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## Language & Runtime
- Use **Python 3.11+** features where appropriate (e.g. `match`/`case`, 
  `tomllib`, improved type hints).
- Specify `python_requires = ">=3.11"` if a `pyproject.toml` is ever added.

## Agent Framework
- Use **Google ADK (`google-adk`)** for all agent definitions — never build 
  agents from scratch with raw `google-generativeai` calls.
- Define every agent as an `Agent` object (from `google.adk.agents`).
- The **default model** for all agents is `gemini-2.5-flash` unless the user 
  explicitly requests a different model.

## API Keys & Secrets
- Load **all** API keys and secrets from environment variables using 
  `python-dotenv` (`from dotenv import load_dotenv`).
- Call `load_dotenv()` at the top of any entry-point file (`app.py`, scripts).
- **NEVER hardcode** keys, tokens, or any credential in any source file.
- Reference `.env.example` to see which environment variables this project uses.

## Code Organisation
- Keep **agent definitions** in `agents/` — one file per agent 
  (e.g. `agents/hello_agent.py`, `agents/code_quality_agent.py`).
- Keep **tool functions** in `tools/` — one file per logical group 
  (e.g. `tools/github_tools.py`, `tools/analysis_tools.py`).
- `app.py` is the main entry point; it imports and wires agents together 
  but contains minimal logic itself.

## Documentation & Comments
- Every **agent file** must have a module-level docstring explaining what the 
  agent does, what model it uses, and what tools it has access to.
- Every **tool function** must have a Google-style docstring with `Args:` 
  and `Returns:` sections.
- Add inline comments for non-obvious logic — this is a **learning/portfolio** 
  project; code should be easy to follow for someone new to ADK.

## Security — Handling Fetched Repo Content
- **NEVER execute, eval, or subprocess-run any code fetched from an external 
  repository.**
- Treat ALL content fetched from GitHub (files, code, configs) strictly as 
  **untrusted plain text / data** to be read and analysed, never run.
- Pass fetched content to the agent as a string in the prompt — do not write 
  it to disk in a way that could be accidentally executed.
- **GitHub MCP Tooling Read-Only Policy:** The GitHub MCP agent must only ever
  be configured with read operations (e.g., listing files, getting file contents).
  Do not enable or execute any write, create, delete, or modify operations on any
  repository.


## Dependency Management
- Pin dependencies loosely (e.g. `>=1.0.0`) in `requirements.txt` so users 
  get the latest compatible versions, but note tested versions in comments 
  when there is a known compatibility constraint.
- Keep a single `requirements.txt` at the project root.

## Formatting
- Follow **PEP 8** style.
- Use 4-space indentation (no tabs).
- Max line length: 100 characters.
